Hi Matt, here is the ppt that has the project summary. And then I'm also
attaching the pdfs of the handouts tying into it all.  - Durlov



---------- Forwarded message ---------
From: Durlov Khan <durlovk001@gmail.com>
Date: Tue, Nov 18, 2025 at 9:53=E2=80=AFPM
Subject: Re: Volunteering for some engineering projects for the classroom
To: Ruth Clifford <ruth.clifford@wellan.org>
Cc: Rachel Levy <rachel.levy@wellan.org>, upperelementary3 <
upperelementary3@wellan.org>


Hi Ruth,

Here's the current presentation that we're using for the 2025-2026 year for
the volunteer projects, attached.

1. The circuit-design-only project will run a little over an hour.
    - for this one, I come with the arduino controller already
pre-programmed with a specific code
    - I have handouts that show what the code tries to do that I go over
with the kids
    - And I have handouts of the circuit that we want to build, that's
supposed to work with that code
    - Then we start building the circuit
    - There is a design caveat that the kids and I together "discover" as
we are building the circuit
    - We make adjustments to our circuit to accommodate the caveat
    - And that's it, the system just works.

2. The full project of coding-and-circuit-design will run close to a couple
hours.
    - this one has the two parts to the problem
    - depending on whether I have assistants, we do division of labor and
some teams will work on the code while an equal number of other teams will
work on the circuit
    - once the coders are ready with their code, and the circuit designers
are ready with their circuit, we connect the laptops to the arduino
controllers to load the programs
    - then we debug what works and what doesn't until we get the system
working
    - if I don't have assistants, then we do code first then circuit and
then debug.

#1 is easier since the only variable with bugs is the circuit.
#2 is more complex since bugs can be in the code, the circuit OR - as in
the case with #1 - the bug could be *between* what the code wants to do and
what the circuit can handle.

Of course, I (and my assistants, if present) help profusely depending on
the students' capabilities so that every system that we design works by the
end and nobody goes home disappointed.

Durlov








